  "prompt": "What is the weirdest thing in space?",
  "response": "Space is full of strange and fascinating phenomena, but one contender for the title of \"weirdest thing\" is the concept of \"dark matter.\" Although it cannot be observed directly, dark matter is thought to make up about 27% of the universe's mass-energy content. Its presence is inferred from gravitational effects on visible matter, such as galaxies and galaxy clusters. \n\nAnother contender is a unique astronomical object known as a \"pulsar.\" These are highly magnetized, rotating neutron stars that emit beams of electromagnetic radiation out of their magnetic poles. As they rotate, these beams sweep across space, and if they align with Earth, they can be detected as regular pulses of radiation, which is why they're called pulsars.\n\nAdditionally, phenomena like the \"Great Attractor,\" a gravitational anomaly in intergalactic space affecting the motion of galaxies, or the existence of \"rogue planets\"\u2014planets that do not orbit a star and drift through space\u2014are other examples of the bizarre aspects of the cosmos.\n\nEach of these examples highlights the incredible variety of strange and still not fully understood phenomena in the universe!",
